Notes: "Relative to availability, wolves selected more males (64%) and fewer females (18%) than expected.". According to femur analysis. wolves generally killed "older infirmed elk"
Wolf_Pack_Notes: Recolonized SA in winter 2002
Prey_Notes: "Putatively naive" at beginning of study period. Male elk expend considerable energy during the rut and probably enter winter in poorer physical condition than female elk,  "Logistic regression results of prey selection (full model) indicated that male elk in poor physical condition were most likely to be killed by wolves". The probability of elk occurrence was lower on south aspects, and was greatest in grasslands and shallow slopes (diminished risk of cougar predation but heightened risk of wold predation). Structural complexity of elk kill sites (wolf) increased over the years. "Elk typically move around winter range in groups of 100–200 females"

Wolf_Pack_Notes: Recolonized SA in winter 2002
Prey_Notes: "Putatively naive" at beginning of study period. The probability of mule deer occurrence was higher on south aspects, shrub steppe habitats, and with increasing slopes (most likely to occur in juniper canyon habitats (characterized by steeper slopes and greater hiding cover ~ little risk of wolf predation), and was lower in riparian and grassland habitats. Grouo size ranges from 1-15 individuals

Notes: moose or elk killed every 2.7 days (moose and elk combined). Using figure extract tool and the text the % of 19 elk kills made up by each age class was: 0.5-1 = 26%, 1.5-2=0%, 2.5-5.5=16%, 6.5-10.5=11%, and 11.5-16.5=46%. Based on the following, RB recalculated the data for the whole time period: "Carcass use during the period of intensive tracking (mid-Feb-mid-Mar) was 56% for elk and 40% for moose (Table 2). Assuming that 75% by weight of a carcass was consumable (Peterson 1977), during this 19-day period 854 kg of elk and 407 kg of moose were available to the BL pack. Actual calculated consumption was 478 kg of elk and 163 kg of moose or 25 and 9/kg/day, respectively. Given an average weight of 32.7 kg/wolf, the study pack of 5 animals consumed 0.21 kg of prey/kg of wolf or 34 kg/pack daily."

Study_Area: Bow Valley of Banff National Park (Bow Valley BNP)
Wolf_Pack_Notes: Pack size between 5-8. Territory is the southern third of the study area
Mass_Details: Calculated for from the authors biomass estimates (no mass values were reported) they used different masses for summer and winter
Prey_Notes: High habitat overlap with wolves. Individual encounter rate of 0.69 (highest od any prey) and group encounter of 0.38 (second highest encounter). Mean herd size of 10.3. Southern half of Bow Valley is an important wintering area for elk. "rarely defend themselves actively (Carbyn 1974), but frequently seek refuge in deep water". May be more detectable to wolves since they are larger, in larger herds, and more frequently occupy more open areas. Flee from wolves.

Study_Area: Bow Valley of Banff National Park (Bow Valley BNP)
Wolf_Pack_Notes: Pack size between 5-8. Territory is the southern third of the study area
Mass_Details: Calculated for from the authors biomass estimates (no mass values were reported) they used different masses for summer and winter
Prey_Notes: Includes both white-tailed and mule deer. High habitat overlap with wolves. Individual encounter rate of 0.22 (second highest of any prey) and group encounter of 0.50 (highest of any prey). Mean herd size of 2.5. Southern half of Bow Valley is an important wintering area for mule deer and white tailed deer. May be less detectable to wolves than elk since they are smaller, in smaller herds, and more frequently occupy more wooded and less open areas . Flee from wolves.

Study_Area: Bow Valley of Banff National Park (Bow Valley BNP)
